<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 12:10<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I29fbc4d0630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>12.</label.designator><headtext>Burdens and Presumptions</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id72176b3682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>12:10.</label.designator><headtext>Conflicting presumptions</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>When presumptions conflict with each other, the stronger prevails, and those of equal weight cancel each other. <eos/><bos/>The stronger presumption is grounded on greater considerations of public policy.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7ba58cf074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">1</footnote.reference>] Georgia has followed this rule.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7ba58cf174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">2</footnote.reference>] For example, <cite.query w-src-number="0287017242" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST19-3-2" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I30d37f7074d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 19-3-2</cite.query> provides that <begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>“[t]he dissolution of a previous marriage in divorce proceedings must be affirmatively established and will not be presumed.”<eos/><end.quote refid="QT_0001"/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Early cases indicated that the proponent of the validity of a second marriage had to make such a showing.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7ba58cf274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">3</footnote.reference>] However, the rule has now been settled and the proponent of the second marriage benefits from a presumption that the marriage is valid until a party proves that a former marriage was valid and that the spouse of the former marriage is still alive. <eos/><bos/>Only then must the proponent of the second marriage go forward with the evidence to show dissolution of the first marriage by divorce.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7ba5b40074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">4</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="I7ba58cf074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017242" w-serial-number="1942105126" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I30d26e0274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Matson v. Crowe, 193 Ga. 578, 19 S.E.2d 288 (1942)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287017242" w-serial-number="1975132578" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I30d2bc2274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Gilbert v. State, 235 Ga. 501, 220 S.E.2d 262 (1975)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7ba58cf174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017242" w-serial-number="1949105017" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I30d3315274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Longstreet v. Longstreet, 205 Ga. 255, 53 S.E.2d 480 (1949)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017242" w-serial-number="1956125840" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I30d3315574d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">McCormick v. Denny, 212 Ga. 444, 93 S.E.2d 578 (1956)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017242" w-serial-number="1947103788" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I30d3315874d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Callaway v. Cox, 74 Ga. App. 555, 40 S.E.2d 578 (1946)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7ba58cf274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017242" w-serial-number="1961125722" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I30d3cd9274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Ganns v. Worrell, 216 Ga. 512, 117 S.E.2d 533 (1960)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017242" w-serial-number="1966131907" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I30d3cd9574d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Murry v. Lett, 222 Ga. 67, 148 S.E.2d 412 (1966)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7ba5b40074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017242" w-serial-number="1973127730" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I30d469d274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Smith v. Smith, 230 Ga. 616, 198 S.E.2d 307 (1973)</cite.query>, stating that the Court of Appeals had correctly decided the question in <cite.query w-src-number="0287017242" w-serial-number="1961126571" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I30d469d574d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Zurich Ins. Co. v. Craft, 103 Ga. App. 889, 120 S.E.2d 922 (1961)</cite.query>, and <cite.query w-src-number="0287017242" w-serial-number="1966132160" w-seq-number="00011" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I30d469d874d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">American Mut. Liability Ins. Co. v. Copeland, 113 Ga. App. 707, 149 S.E.2d 402 (1966)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017242" w-serial-number="1973127730" w-seq-number="00012" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I30d5543274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Smith</ital></cite.query> was followed in <cite.query w-src-number="0287017242" w-serial-number="1976136392" w-seq-number="00013" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I30d5543574d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Patrick v. Simon, 237 Ga. 742, 229 S.E.2d 746 (1976)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017242" w-serial-number="1979127637" w-seq-number="00014" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I30d5543874d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Uddyback v. Johnson, 149 Ga. App. 769, 256 S.E.2d 29 (1979)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017242" w-serial-number="1984128958" w-seq-number="00015" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I30d5543b74d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Baker v. Musa, 170 Ga. App. 77, 316 S.E.2d 178 (1984)</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287017242" w-serial-number="1984148255" w-seq-number="00016" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I30d5543e74d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Spann v. Clark, 171 Ga. App. 690, 320 S.E.2d 822 (1984)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017242" w-serial-number="1984157914" w-seq-number="00017" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I30d5544174d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Glover v. Glover, 172 Ga. App. 278, 322 S.E.2d 755 (1984)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287017242" w-serial-number="1975132936" w-seq-number="00018" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I30d5c96274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Edwards v. Edwards, 136 Ga. App. 668, 222 S.E.2d 169 (1975)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 12:10<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
